<h1>Mila Makovec: <span>A Tailor-Made Therapy</span></h1>

<p class="hero-sub">
From rare disease genomics to individualized medicine.
</p>

<div class="story-image">
  <img
    src="/mila-makovec-rare-disease-genomics.jpeg"
    alt="Mila Makovec during rare disease treatment"
  >
  <p class="credit">
    Photo: Katherine C. Cohen / Boston Children’s Hospital, via STAT.
  </p>
</div>

<section class="section">

<h2>From Rare Disease to <span>Genomic Discovery</span></h2>

<p>
Mila Makovec’s story became one of the most important examples of individualized genomic medicine. As a young child, Mila experienced progressive neurological symptoms, including vision loss, movement difficulties, seizures, and developmental regression. After an intensive diagnostic search, she was diagnosed with Batten disease, a rare and severe neurodegenerative genetic disorder.
</p>

<p>
Batten disease belongs to a group of inherited disorders that affect cellular waste processing and neurological function. In Mila’s case, researchers identified disease-associated changes involving the CLN7 gene. Her diagnosis showed how whole-genome sequencing can reveal hidden genetic causes when standard testing does not fully explain a child’s condition.
</p>

</section>

<section class="section">

<h2>A Historic <span>Search for Answers</span></h2>

<p>
Mila’s mother, Julia Vitarello, became an advocate for her daughter and searched for scientists who could help identify the complete molecular cause of Mila’s disease. That effort eventually connected the family with Dr. Timothy Yu at Boston Children’s Hospital.
</p>

<p>
Dr. Yu’s team used whole-genome sequencing to identify a rare mutation that disrupted Mila’s CLN7 gene. This finding provided the molecular foundation for a highly individualized therapeutic strategy designed specifically around Mila’s genetic alteration.
</p>

</section>

<section class="section">

<h2>A New Chapter in <span>Personalized Medicine</span></h2>

<p>
The therapy developed for Mila was an antisense oligonucleotide, a type of molecular therapy designed to bind RNA and influence how genetic instructions are processed. The treatment was named “milasen” after Mila.
</p>

<p>
Milasen was developed under an unusually rapid and individualized pathway. Reports from the time described improvements in seizure burden and alertness after treatment began, while also emphasizing that the therapy was experimental, highly specific to Mila’s mutation, and not a general cure for Batten disease.
</p>

</section>

<section class="section">

<h2>The Omics <span>Connection</span></h2>

<p>
Mila Makovec’s story connects directly to the omics sciences because it shows how genome sequencing, molecular diagnosis, RNA biology, and therapeutic design can converge around one patient’s disease mechanism.
</p>

<p>
Her case demonstrated both the promise and complexity of precision medicine. It showed that genomic information can sometimes move beyond diagnosis and help guide the design of a personalized therapeutic approach, while also raising important scientific, ethical, regulatory, and access questions.
</p>

</section>

<section class="section">

<h2>Why Her Story <span>Matters</span></h2>

<p>
Mila’s journey helped define what “N-of-1” medicine can mean: one patient, one rare mutation, and one therapy designed around a specific molecular cause. Her story became a landmark example of how rare disease research can push the boundaries of genomic medicine.
</p>

<p>
At PanorOmics, we believe Mila Makovec’s story shows why omics sciences matter in real life. Genomic data is not only information stored in a database. In the right scientific and clinical context, it can help families find answers, guide research, and open new possibilities for individualized medicine.
</p>

